title: Chapter 4: An Unprecedented Experimental Facility
content:
Chapter 4:
An Unprecedented Experimental Facility

LOOKING AT THE bundles of bills arranged on the white table, Mika let out a sigh of admiration.

"There's fifty million. I've prepared it in cash as you wished. There's no trace."

I told Mika without meeting her eyes.

It was the amount after deducting all expenses for childbirth and hospitalization during pregnancy.

"Politicians really have control over money and everything else, don't they? It must have been easy for you to prepare fifty million."

Dressed in a suit she probably wasn't used to wearing, Mika spoke without sarcasm.

"Money is heavy, but I can prepare as much as necessary to live. That's what the world's like on this side."

Mika laughed in amazement at my matter-of-fact, businesslike demeanor.

"So, the fact that your own child was born doesn't affect your heart at all, does it?"

"Then, are you going to tell me you've suddenly awakened to motherhood?"

"Of course not. If that were the case, I wouldn't hand over the child. For me, the whole process of carrying and giving birth to that child was just a job, nothing more, nothing less."

I was relieved to hear that.

Not because of Mika's dominance, but because I could see she was telling the truth by looking into her eyes.

"It seems I was right to choose you."

"Well, whether it was worth the job is another matter. I started to regret it when my stomach got bigger and the morning sickness got worse. I came here thinking of complaining, but seeing all this money, I don't seem to care anymore."

Even for Mika, who had been earning over a million a month, fifty million in one lump sum seemed to have made a difference. Though, I would be troubled if she complained. Considering the normal price for surrogacy and the like, even if you estimated it on the higher end of the range, I was paying more than double the market rate.

"Normally, I'd have to pay nearly half of this to the government."

"It seems so. To save fifty million, you need to earn about a hundred million, right? Tax taking nearly half the amount—I can't help but think it's crazy."

While being amazed, Mika touched the surface of the stack of bills and gave a small smile.

"Have you ever properly paid taxes?"

People often said that individuals in Mika's line of work didn't pay taxes.

"I hardly remember ever doing so. Well, maybe I'll pay them when I start a new job, so it's fine. More importantly, how have you been lately, Atsuomi? No changes?"

"I'm busy, so I'm not in the mood for a long conversation. Let's proceed with what needs to be done."

I took out the contract and presented it in front of Mika.

"If you take the money, sign here. You have rights over the child only until you write your name."

"You worry too much. It's okay, I had the child just for the money. I have no doubts."

Mika had no intention of refusing the stacked money and reaffirmed her intention to accept it.

"No matter what, you will never be recognized as the mother in the future."

It might've seemed persistent, but this was a very important matter.

If Mika, who was well-versed in the underworld, tried to openly retrieve the child, the White Room's existence could be exposed.

"I understand. Don't tell the child about me."

"There's no reason to—and no need."

"Hey, can you at least tell me what will happen to the child from now on?"

I hadn't told Mika anything about the White Room.

She was only curious about the child's future—that was understandable.

"That's none of your business. Once the contract is finalized, our connection ends."

"Alright, alright."

Understanding it was futile, Mika signed the contract.

"Is this good?"

From her writing pressure, it was clear she held no hesitation until the end.

After putting this much emphasis on things, there shouldn't be any remaining doubts.

I gave instructions to load the money-filled suitcase into the trunk of Mika's car.

Carrying such a large sum in cash was somewhat risky, but both Mika and I agreed to avoid bank transfers.

"Well then, I'm leaving."

This would be the last time I would meet and exchange words with Mika.

As I was about to silently see her off, Mika stopped after a few steps.

"Aren't you going to ask what I'm going to do from now on?"

I couldn't read what expression she wore.

Though, I was able to sense that her voice contained a slight hint of emotion.

"I'm not interested. Whether you go under that host or take the money and fly overseas, it's your freedom."

She seemed slightly surprised but laughed as if she understood.

"You knew? About me and him?"

"Even without me investigating, the people around me will look into everything themselves."

"Since when did you learn of it?"

"I knew before I proposed the marriage and childbirth ideas to you."

"Did you ever suspect the kid wasn't yours?"

Mika narrowed her eyes as if she were about to play a prank.

"It's a matter beyond suspicion. If it were you, you would've anticipated that I'd conduct a paternal test. If it turned out to be someone else's child, you would lose the payment. It's an impossible choice."

"Heh, indeed."

"However, you controlled yourself well. During our marriage, you kept your meetings with him to a minimum and were cautious not to be caught."

Whether that host truly intended to make Mika happy, I didn't know.

At the very least, including this fifty million, Mika's assets must've been over two hundred million.

Whether it was five years or ten years, a happy life with the host was guaranteed until the money ran out.

"Atsuomi, did you ever think you loved me, even once?"

"You would do anything for money and yourself. That's the highest praise I can give you."

"Isn't that off-topic…? No, maybe that's the whole answer."

I never harbored any special feelings for Mika.

At the same time, this woman had no lingering feelings for me either.

All her seemingly sympathetic words here were just an act to make herself look better.

She preferred young men with good looks and a knack for speaking, and above all, she valued both money and herself the most.

That was the woman named Mika.

"Goodbye, Atsuomi."

"Wait. This is a celebration gift from me."

I added three million yen to the originally prepared reward.

With what people might call severance money, I handed it over to Mika.

"You don't have to do that, I won't sell this story to the tabloids. After all, I've done plenty of underhanded things with you, Atsuomi."

Mika too had many things that would cause trouble if brought to light.

"That's right. That's why this is purely a celebratory gift, one without any ulterior motives. If you don't need it, you don't have to force yourself to accept it."

As I was about to take the money back, Mika stopped my hand with a laugh.

"There's no such thing as having too much money when building a home. The price of land keeps rising, doesn't it?"

"Why do you think the land prices are soaring? You don't even know the underlying reasons, do you?"

"I don't know. I'm not interested. As long as I have money, that's all that matters."

"That's so like you. Though, you should know, it will be a while before you can officially marry someone."

"That's because I'm supposed to go back to the countryside as your wife, right?"

For a while, we needed to maintain the appearance of a married couple until the child was enrolled in the White Room.

"It won't be long. Just wait another two years, and after that, you can do whatever you want."

For that reason, I handed Mika a divorce form, filled out except for our respective dates.

"Lastly, if you've decided on a name, I'll fill out things using that name."

Eleven days had passed since the birth, and without additional procedures, only three days remained.

"I have no rights to the child, yet you're letting me decide?"

"Names are just symbols. No matter who assigns them, a person's essence doesn't change."

After a moment of hesitation, Mika spoke the child's name.

"Then… Kiyotaka. Name him Kiyotaka."

"That suggestion is very like you."

It was an unexpected turn of events, and I was slightly surprised.

"I thought it might be a name that stays in your memory."

"Alright. I'll register it as such."

"You're really always so calm, with such a cold heart. Normally, people would get angry here. Naming him after the host I'm into… You're not sane."

Mika began to walk away. This time, she didn't stop.

"Goodbye, Atsuomi. The time I spent with you has been a valuable experience for me, for better or worse."

After Mika left, I wrote "Kiyotaka" in the register.

With that amount of money in her hands, she shouldn't have had any complaints.

As the head of the White Room, I had offered up my own child.

If I could achieve that, then the money spent was a cheap purchase.

As long as Kiyotaka was useful for about five years, even if he were to break down after that, it wouldn't be a problem.

There was no need for my own child to excel.

"What a charming woman she was, Ayanokouji-san."

Tsukishiro, who had been waiting in the next room over, appeared with his usual smile.

"You've had a hard time too, playing as a detective."

"I'm a jack-of-all-trades. Though, are you truly sure you can trust her? If necessary, it would be wise for you to consider disposing of her. As long as she has money, she'll behave, but with her behavior, she might run out in a few years. Or perhaps a man will run off with a large sum?"

Yes, humans were unpredictable.

When she loses her money in the future, Mika might appear before me again.

But I hope, being wise as you are, you won't choose that.

Even the most worthless, filthy soul shouldn't vanish without purpose.

"It's standard to take the initiative, but it depends on the time and situation. Mika cutting off communication also creates other risks. For now, it's necessary that she remains present as a mother."

Given the circumstances, it was clear that I had no attachment to the child. If the person who was legally my wife exposed this, my credibility in the financial world would be lost in an instant.

"Indeed. It's as you say."

"In a few more days, the child would be delivered to us after he's completed the tests. He will begin the experiments as a fourth-generation participant."

It seems that a harsh life awaits your son, just like you.

Though it sounded like words of pity, Tsukishiro had not the slightest trace of such emotions.
